Front sight inserts in cosmolined pouch. 25” free floating barrel.These rifles are among the finest you can get and are widely sought after by both collectors and target shooters alike.Produced for the US Army from 1987-1990, Kimber of Oregon contracted these single-shot rifles. title: For Sale:  Master Engraved Colt Mod 1911 Semi-Auto Pistol
postcontent: Serial # 172007 5" barrel in .45 ACP caliber. Made in 1917. This pistol originated as a standard U.S. Army Model 1911 in 1917. It comes with a letter from master engraver David Wade Harris of Jacksonville, Texas listing this gun by serial number as to work performed by him, to include: full coverage American scroll with platinum inlays in blued finish. David has signed his work at the rear right side of frame "D.W. Harris". Harris studied under Weldon Bledsoe, who studied under Cole Agee. Harris is featured in the Cole Agee book on page 133 to 136. This pistol retains all of its original 1917 era parts, in which Harris has tastefully performed his craft with full coverage scroll engraving. It is outlined in platinum with an inset platinum arrow on top of slide. It was then finished in full blue finish and fitted with a pair of silver medallion ivory grips. Harris is considered one of the master engravers of our time and this lovely pistol proved to be a perfect canvas for this engraving style. Strong clean bore and fine action. It is in as new condition, having not been fired since work was performed.$10,000.00Reasonable offers entertained.

title: For Sale:  Poorman's Scout Rifle / Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
I have a 1943 Izhevsk M91/30 for sale.  It has been modified into a poor man’s scout rifle. 
A few years back, I was on a mini-prepper kick and decided to try to make the best rifle possible based on durability, accuracy, ease of use, and abundance of parts.  The catch was that I gave myself a financial ceiling of $500.  Naturally, that led to the venerated M91/30.  This was the best shooting of the four that I owned at the time.  Altogether, I came in at about $420 for the whole set up, including the cost of the rifle.
I removed the front and rear sights with equal parts brute force and loving tenderness.  Once they were off, I placed a Bushnell pistol scope on the existing dove tail that the rear sight ramp is usually pinned to.  I used the beefiest rings that I could find to mitigate the kick of Russian aggression that is transferred to your shoulder when you fire the M91/30.   The front sight was taken off as well.  Then I installed an ATI Monte Carlo type stock.
The end result was/is a fairly impressive shooting rifle.  The stock absorbs a good amount of the punishment, making it not too miserable the day after shooting a few rounds.  I’m able to get 2.5’’ groups at 100 yards, despite the fact that I’m not the best shot in the world.Here's a photo of the group I shot after I did all the work. https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B36N6uTeC5o1LUNsOTFZaHkwSFU
Included in this sale is everything pictured plus a sling, ammo pouch, and whatever other Mosin Nagant paraphernalia I can dig up.  I lost the oil cans.  Sorry.
I may consider trades if the right thing pops up, but money talks.  You know you want to own this badass piece of Bubba’s best gunsmith work.
